West Germany said it would accept asuperpower plan to ban medium and shorter-range nuclearmissiles in Europe provided Bonn was allowed to retain its ownshorter-range missiles.    After six weeks of public wrangling over the so-called"double-zero" offer, Chancellor Helmut Kohl's coalition finallysaid it would agree to an East-West ban on shorter-rangenuclear missiles.    But in a statement issued after top-level talks, thegovernment said Bonn wanted the 72 West German Pershing-1amissiles excluded from an East-West accord -- a demanddiplomats said could produce a snag in the Geneva arms talks. Reuter&#3;